Note that, by contrast, $N \widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$ is asymptotically bounded above by $(1 / a+1 /(1-a))(1 / 4)$, since $V(0)$ and $V(1)$ in the Theorem A. 2 are each no larger than $1 / 4$. In the worst case, this pair of facts suggests that unbiased estimators can have exponentially worse scaling with $K$ than the naive variance estimator.

We ask: is exponential growth of $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ ldiosyncratic, or unavoidable? We now formally show that this finding is in fact generic, for any capacity-constrained platform experiment of the type we consider in this paper, with a monotone treatment: the exponential increase in variance for any unbiased estimator is unavoidable for the practitioner. Establishing such a result generically requires construction of an appropriate sequence of capacity-constrained platforms with monotone treatments. In the following theorem, we consider a sequence of treatment and control systems that approach an appropriate "mean-field" limits, respectively, as $K \rightarrow \infty$. We use this limiting to show that for any such sequence, regardless of parameters, the Cramér-Rao lower bound $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ grows exponentially in the size of the state space. The proof of the theorem can be found in Appendix A. 4 .

Theorem 5.3. Fix $\bar{\lambda}>0$, and continuous functions $\bar{p}_{0}, \bar{p}_{1}, \bar{\tau}:[0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ such that $0<\bar{p}_{0}(s)<$ $\bar{p}_{1}(s)<1$ for all $s<1 ; \bar{p}_{0}, \bar{p}_{1}$ are strictly decreasing; $\bar{\tau}(s)>0$ for all $s>0$; and $\bar{\tau}$ is nondecreasing. Further, assume that $\bar{p}_{z}(1)=0$, and $\bar{\tau}_{z}(0)=0$.

For each $K=1,2, \ldots$, define the following quantities:

1. $\lambda^{(K)}=K \bar{\lambda}$;
2. $\tau^{(K)}(x)=K \bar{\tau}(x / K)$, for $x=0, \ldots K$;
3. $p_{z}^{(K)}(x)=\bar{p}_{z}(x / K)$, for $z=0,1$, and $x=0, \ldots, K$.

Then for each $K$, this defines a pair of control and treatment systems with strictly monotone (positive) treatment. Let $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{z}^{(K)}, z=0,1$ be the stationary distribution of the global control and global treatment Markov chains, respectively; and let $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{a}^{(K)}$ be the stationary distribution of the experiment chain, with treatment probability a (where $0<a<1$ ).

Let $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}(K)$ denote the Cramér-Rao lower bound for the $K^{\prime}$ the system. Then there exists constants $C>0$ and $\gamma>1$ (which depend on the system parameters $\bar{\lambda}, \bar{p}_{0}, \bar{p}_{1}$, and $\bar{\tau}$ ) such that for all $K$ :

$$
\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}(K) \geq C \gamma^{K}
$$

Note that the same theorem can be adapted to a strictly negative treatment, by changing the role of $\mathbf{p}_{0}$ and $\mathbf{p}_{1}$; we omit the details.

Taken together, Theorems 5.1, 5.2, and 5.3 indicate that if treatments are strictly monotone, then the power of the test statistic using the DM estimator and the associated naive variance estimator will be much higher than the power of any test statistic using an unbiased estimator. We use a numerical example to illustrate this phenomenon.

Numerics. For the remainder of this section, we use numerics to study two questions:

1. How does the Cramér-Rao bound $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ compare to the scaled limit of the naive variance estimator (as $N \rightarrow \infty$ ) as the number of listings grows?

2. How does the rate at which the false negative probability of $\hat{T}_{N}$ converges to 1 compare to the corresponding rate for an optimal unbiased test statistic $\hat{U}_{N}$ as the number of customers grows?

We start by noting that for any unbiased estimator $\hat{\theta}_{N}$, since $N \operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\theta}_{N}\right) \geq \sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$, we conclude that:

$$
\left|\hat{U}_{N}\right| \leq \frac{\sqrt{N}\left|\hat{\theta}_{N}\right|}{\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}}
$$

We leverage this bound in our numerics to study the performance of unbiased estimation. In particular, for the remainder of the section we assume that $\hat{\theta}_{N}$ is an optimal unbiased estimator, so it obeys the following central limit theorem:

$$
\frac{\sqrt{N}\left(\hat{\theta}_{N}-\mathrm{GTE}\right)}{\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}} \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}(0,1)
$$

as $N \rightarrow \infty$. For general unbiased estimators, the limiting variance will be larger than 1 , since the true variance of $\hat{\theta}_{N}$ is lower bounded by $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2} / N$. Using this limit, it is straightforward to check that for any treatment such that $\mathbf{p}_{1} \neq \mathbf{p}_{0}$, the power of the decision rule (15) when (24) holds is asymptotically approximately:

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(W>\Phi_{\alpha / 2}-\frac{\sqrt{N} \mathrm{GTE}}{\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}}\right)+\mathbb{P}\left(W<-\Phi_{\alpha / 2}-\frac{\sqrt{N} \mathrm{GTE}}{\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}}\right)
$$

where $W$ is a standard normal random variable and $\Phi_{\alpha / 2}$ is the upper $\alpha / 2$-quantile of the standard normal distribution. We use this calculation in our numerics below.

We consider a CR experiment with $K$-dependent arrival rate $\lambda^{(K)}=K \bar{\lambda}$, constant $K$-dependent death rates $\boldsymbol{\tau}^{(K)(k)}=K \bar{\tau}$ for all $k$, and $a=0.5$. We set $\bar{\lambda}=1.5$ and $\bar{\tau}=1$; for further details on the numerics we refer the reader to Section C of the appendix. We construct a $K$-dependent positive treatment using the logit booking probability model of [30]. In particular, we suppose that a control customer receives value $v_{0}=0.5$ from booking a listing, and that a treatment customer receives value $v_{1}=v_{0}+\delta$ for booking a listing. All customers have outside option $\epsilon^{(K)}=K \bar{\epsilon}$ for leaving the platform without booking a listing. If the customer arrives to the platform with $k$ listings booked, then the control and treatment booking probabilities respectively are given by:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& p_{0}^{(K)}(k)=\frac{(K-k) v_{0}}{\epsilon^{(K)}+(K-k) v_{0}} \\
& p_{1}^{(K)}(k)=\frac{(K-k) v_{1}}{\epsilon^{(K)}+(K-k) v_{1}}=\frac{(K-k)\left(v_{0}+\delta\right)}{\epsilon^{(K)}+(K-k)\left(v_{0}+\delta\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

For the numerics in this section we fix $\bar{\epsilon}=1$ and $\delta=0.05$, which leads to control steady state booking probability $\rho_{0}=0.332$, treatment steady state booking probability $\rho_{1}=0.354$, and thus a GTE of $\rho_{1}-\rho_{0}=0.022$.

For the first set of numerics, we let $K$ vary from 100 to 300; in Appendix C. 2 we vary the other model parameters. For each value of $K$, we compute the scaled limit of the naive variance estimator $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$ given in Theorem A.2, as well as the lower bound $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ given in Theorem A. 4 in Appendix A.3. Figure 1 shows that as the number of listings grows, the bound $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ grows exponentially with $K$, consistent with Theorem 5.3; by contrast, the scaled limit of the naive variance estimator, given by $(1 / a) V(1)+1 /(1-a) V(0)$ (cf. Theorem A.2) remains bounded.

# 6 Non-monotone treatments 

Our analysis thus far has shown that if treatments are monotone, then even without debiasing, a platform is able to control false positive probability (Section 4) while obtaining higher power than any debiased estimation approach (Section 5). In this section, we use numerics to investigate the behavior of false positive probability and statistical power when interventions are non-monotone.

In general, if interventions are non-monotone, it is possible for both quantities to behave arbitrarily worse using the naïve decision-making approach based on the difference-in-means estimator, compared to the decision rule associated to an optimal unbiased estimator. In particular, there exist examples where the false positive probability can become arbitrarily close to 1 , instead of being controlled at the desired pre-specified level in the decision rule (15); and there also exist examples where the statistical power remains bounded away from 1, regardless of how many samples are collected - in contrast to the performance of a decision rule that uses an unbiased estimator.

To illustrate these possibilities, we consider a natural class of interventions that are nonmonotone, where booking probabilities are increased in lower states (i.e., when many listings are available), and are decreased in larger states (i.e., when few listings are available). These are natural interventions to consider from an operations standpoint. For example, a ridesharing platform may be interested in understanding the impact on rides if prices are lowered relative to the status quo when ample driver supply is available, but raised relative to the status quo when driver supply is relatively tightly constrained.

Concretely, we construct two extreme examples of this form, to illustrate the potential worstcase consequences for false positive probability and statistical power, respectively.
Example 6.1. $\left(\mathrm{ADE}_{a}<0\right.$ but GTE $=0$.) In the first example, we set $\bar{\lambda}=1, \bar{\tau}=1$, and $K=100$. We set control booking probabilities $\mathbf{p}_{0}$ as follows:

$$
p_{0}(k)=0.5 \text { if } k<K, p_{0}(K)=0
$$

(We note in passing that booking probabilities are not strictly decreasing, as in Assumption 3.1, but this is not essential; similar examples can be constructed even if booking probabilities are required to be strictly monotone.) We set treatment booking probabilities as follows:

$$
p_{1}(k)=\bar{p} \text { if } k=0,1 ; p_{1}(k)=0.1 \text { if } 2 \leq k<K, p_{1}(K)=0
$$

where $\bar{p}>0.5$; we show how to choose $\bar{p}$ to ensure that $\mathrm{GTE}=0$. In other words, when the system is nearly empty, the treatment raises booking probabilities relative to control. Otherwise, the treatment lowers booking probabilities relative to control.

To construct $\bar{p}$, we first note that it is straightforward to use the detailed-balance equations to check that a sufficient condition for $\mathrm{GTE}=0$ is:

$$
1+\bar{p}+\bar{p}^{2} \frac{1-0.1^{K}}{1-0.1}=\frac{1-0.5^{K}}{1-0.5}
$$

Letting $A_{K}=\frac{1-0.1^{K}}{0.9}$ and $B_{K}=\frac{1-0.5^{K}}{0.5}$, we see that $\bar{p}$ solves

$$
A_{K} \bar{p}^{2}+\bar{p}-\left(B_{K}-1\right)=0
$$

so in particular we can set

$$
\bar{p}=\frac{-1+\sqrt{1+4 A_{K}\left(B_{K}-1\right)}}{2 A_{K}}
$$

For $K=100$, we have $\bar{p} \approx 0.6$, and with these parameters and $a=1 / 2$ we have $\mathrm{GTE}=0$ yet $\mathrm{ADE}_{a}=-0.009<0$.

We simulate a Bernoulli randomized experiment with $a=1 / 2$ and $N \in[100,5000]$, with the remaining parameters specified in the previous paragraph. For each fixed set of parameters (ie. fixed $N$ ), we run $5 \times 10^{4}$ trajectories of the experiment, and at each trajectory we form the test statistic (14) using $\widehat{\text { GTE }}$ and $\widehat{\text { Var. }}$. We obtain the false positive probability for the naive test statistic by taking the average number of times $H_{0}$ is rejected under significance level $\alpha=0.05$ over the $5 \times 10^{4}$ trajectories.

As argued above, the treatments constructed in Example 6.1 produce $\mathrm{ADE}_{a}=-0.009<0$ and $\mathrm{GTE}=0$. As a consequence, this is a treatment where the null hypothesis $H_{0}$ is satisfied. (Note that $\mathrm{GTE}=0$ despite the fact that the treatment and control chains are distinct; this is only possible because the treatment is non-monotone, cf. the discussion in Section 3.5.) However, because $\mathrm{ADE}_{a}<0$, the magnitude of the mean of the test statistic $\bar{T}_{N}$ (cf. (14)) grows without bound. As a consequence, the false positive probability of the test statistic $\bar{T}_{N}$ will increase towards 1 as $N \rightarrow \infty$, as suggested by Figure 3. Of course, a test statistic $\bar{U}_{N}$ using an unbiased estimator for GTE along with its true variance (cf. (22)) should control the false positive probability correctly, as long as an appropriate central limit theorem holds.

Example 6.2. $\left(\mathrm{ADE}_{a} \approx 0\right.$ but $\mathrm{GTE}>0$.) In the second example, we set $\bar{\lambda}=1, \bar{\tau}=1$, and $K=30$. We set control booking probabilities $\mathbf{p}_{0}$ as follows:

$$
p_{0}(k)=0.5 \text { if } k<K ; p_{0}(K)=0
$$

(Again note that booking probabilities are not strictly decreasing, as in Assumption 3.1, but again, this is not essential.) We set treatment booking probabilities as follows:

$$
p_{1}(k)=0.62 \text { if } k=0,1 ; p_{1}(k)=0.0745 \text { if } 2 \leq k<K ; p_{1}(K)=0
$$

Again, when the system is nearly empty, the treatment raises booking probabilities relative to control, and otherwise, the treatment lowers booking probabilities relative to control.

This effect is illustrated in Figure 4.

# 7 Conclusion 

Using a benchmark Markov chain model for a two-sided platform, our results characterize the impact of interference on the false positive probability and statistical power when the experimenter uses naïve estimation based on a t-test statistic. We obtain the surprising finding that when treatments are monotone in a CR experiment, the false positive probability is correctly controlled despite the presence of interference, and that the statistical power is larger than that achieved by using an unbiased estimator. In other words, in this setting the platform is actually better off not using a debiased estimator. Despite these findings, as the numerics in Section 6 suggest, if the treatment is not necessarily monotone then in the worst case, a debiased estimation method can offer significant improvements to control of false positive probability, and/or much higher statistical power, than the naive approach.

Several important directions of work remain. First, our paper considers customer-randomized (CR) experiments; it is natural to also consider whether similar results hold for listing-randomized

Given the generality of our results on A/A tests in Section 4.1, we expect that with an appropriate definition of monotone treatments for listing-randomized experiments, similar results as this paper could be obtained.

Second, in our model in Section 3, customers are heterogeneous but listings are homogeneous. It is natural to consider an extension of our model to a setting where listings are heterogeneous as well. (Indeed, development and analysis of LR experiments would require this model extension, to appropriately study a mix of treatment and control listings that are simultaneously in different states of availability.) As for LR experiments, considering listing heterogeneity would also require an appropriate extension of the definition of monotone treatments given in this paper. Interestingly, we conjecture that similar findings as in Section 6 might be obtained in models where listings are heterogeneous, if treatment increases the preference of customers for some types of listings while decreasing their interest in other types of listings. For example, this might be the case if an online labor platform provides the opportunity for workers to display badges and skill certifications on their profile: the resulting change might lead prospective employers to favor certified highly skilled workers over uncertified workers. In such a setting, it would similarly be possible to construct examples where $\mathrm{GTE}=0$ but $\mathrm{ADE} \neq 0$, or $\mathrm{GTE} \neq 0$ but $\mathrm{ADE}=0$-leading to similar qualitative conclusions as our numerics with non-monotone treatments in Section 6.

More broadly, our paper has assumed a particular frequentist hypothesis testing decision-making pipeline, and in particular the use of this pipeline presumes the decision maker cares about type I and type II errors. In practice, there are many reasons this may not be the desired objective, in which case debiasing may be quite valuable. The most obvious such case is when the platform cares

about the actual value of GTE itself; this may be important if launching an intervention carries with it a significant cost, creating a tradeoff for the platform. As an example, a ride-sharing platform may consider the launch of an incentive program for drivers. Even if GTE $>0$, the platform may only be willing to launch if the cost of supporting such an incentive is not prohibitive relative to the true magnitude of GTE. In this case, debiasing is critical to understand the relative tradeoff between the treatment effect and the cost. A similar situation arises if there are multiple target metrics of interest, and the decision maker faces tradeoffs between the impacts to these objectives. For example, a platform testing an change in prices or fees may be interested not only in the change in bookings, but also the change in revenue or profit; recent work has studied the impact of naive experiments and estimation approaches on decision-making in such settings [11].

Indeed, in practice there are a wide range of potential objectives for a platform that uses A/B experimentation. The primary lesson of our work is that the value of debiasing depends on both the desired inferential goal and decision objective, as well as the nature of the treatment itself. ${ }^{1}$ Our work serves provides a framework and essential insights for platforms to make choices regarding their inferential and decision-making pipeline in practice.

# A Experiments on Markov chains 

In this self-contained appendix we consider a setting where the treatment and control data generating processes are Markov chains, with rewards also potentially affected by treatment. We provide a central limit theorem for the DM estimator in the setting of general A/B tests, and then specialize our results to A/A tests. Throughout this appendix, $\rightarrow^{p}$ denotes convergence in probability; $\Rightarrow$ denotes convergence in distribution; and $\mathcal{N}(m, V)$ denotes a normal random variable with mean $m$ and variance $V$. We conclude by showing that the capacity constrained platform model studied in Section 3 is a special case of this setting.

## A. 1 Experiments and estimation on general Markov chains

We first present a general model of A/B tests when the data generating processes in treatment and control are Markov chains. We prove a corresponding central limit theorem for $\widehat{\mathrm{GTb}}_{N}$, and also characterize asymptotics of $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$.

State. We consider homogeneous Markov chains that evolve on a finite state space $S$. We let $X_{1}, X_{2}, \ldots \in S$ denote the sequence of states visited by the chain.

Bernoulli treatment assignment. As in the main text, we let $Z_{1}, Z_{2}, \ldots$ be i.i.d. Bernoulli $(a)$ random variables, with $0<a<1$.

Markov property and transition probabilities. At each time step $i$, we consider an order of events where, given the state $X_{i}$ and the treatment assignment $Z_{i}$, the next state $X_{i+1}$ is realized.

Formally, suppose that $X_{1}=x_{1}, \ldots, X_{i-1}=x_{i-1}, X_{i}=x$, and $Z_{1}=z_{1}, \ldots, Z_{i-1}=z_{i-1}, Z_{i}=z$. The Markov property asserts that:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i+1}=x^{\prime} \mid X_{i}=x, Z_{i}=z\right)= \\
& \qquad \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i+1}=x^{\prime} \mid X_{1}=x_{1}, \ldots, X_{i-1}=x_{i-1}, X_{i}=x ; Z_{1}=z_{1}, \ldots, Z_{i-1}=z_{i-1}, Z_{i}=z\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

We write $P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid z\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(X_{i+1}=x^{\prime} \mid X_{i}=x, Z_{i}=z\right)$. Note that this quantity is independent of $i$, so the transition probabilities are stationary in time; in other words, the Markov chain is homogeneous. Note that since treatment assignments are i.i.d. Bernoulli $(a)$, the sequence $\left\{X_{i}\right\}$ is also a discretetime Markov chain; through an abuse of notation, we represent its transition matrix as $P(\cdot, \cdot \mid a)$, and we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid a\right) & =a \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i+1}=x^{\prime} \mid X_{i}=x, Z_{i}=1\right)+(1-a) \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i+1}=x^{\prime} \mid X_{i}=x, Z_{i}=0\right) \\
& =a P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid 1\right)+(1-a) P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid 0\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

We assume for $z=0,1$ that the transition matrix $P(\cdot, \cdot \mid z)$ is irreducible; therefore for $0<$ $a<1, P(\cdot, \cdot \mid a)$ is also irreducible. Since treatment assignments are i.i.d. Bernoulli $(a)$, if we let $W_{i}=\left(X_{i}, Z_{i}\right)$, then the Markov chain $\left\{W_{i}\right\}$ then has the following transition matrix $R$ :

$$
R\left(x, z ; x^{\prime}, z^{\prime}\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(X_{i+1}=x^{\prime}, Z_{i+1}=z^{\prime} \mid X_{i}=x, Z_{i}=z\right)=a^{z^{\prime}}(1-a)^{1-z^{\prime}} P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid z\right)
$$

It then follows that as long as $0<a<1$, the matrix $R$ is irreducible on the state space $S \times\{0,1\}$.
Invariant distribution. The transition matrix $R$ possesses a unique invariant distribution $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}$. This distribution can be written as follows:

$$
\nu_{a}(x, z)=a^{z}(1-a)^{1-z} \phi_{a}(x)
$$

where $\phi_{a}(x \mid z)$ satisfies:

$$
\phi_{a}(x)=\sum_{x^{\prime}} \sum_{z^{\prime}=0,1} \nu_{a}\left(x^{\prime}, z^{\prime}\right) P\left(x^{\prime}, x \mid z^{\prime}\right)
$$

It is straightforward to verify that $\boldsymbol{\phi}_{a}$ is the invariant distribution of the transition matrix $P(\cdot, \cdot \mid a)$. We use the subscript $a$ to indicate the treatment fraction. Note that in steady state, the distribution of the state under $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}$ is independent of the treatment assignment; this reflects the fact that treatment assignments are i.i.d.

Throughout our analysis, we write $\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}$ for expectations when the initial state $\left(X_{1}, Z_{1}\right)$ is sampled from the invariant distribution $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}$. Except in the context of such expectations, we make no assumptions otherwise on the initial state of the chain.

For completeness, for $a=0,1$ we define $\boldsymbol{\phi}_{0}, \boldsymbol{\phi}_{1}$ to be the invariant distributions of the chain with transition matrix $P(\cdot, \cdot \mid 0), P(\cdot, \cdot \mid 1)$, respectively, i.e., for $a=0,1, \phi_{a}(x)=\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) P\left(x^{\prime}, x \mid a\right)$. These are the invariant distributions for global control $(a=0)$ and global treatment $(a=1)$.

Reward function. We fix a reward function $g(x, z)$ that depends on the state and treatment indicator, and we let $Y_{i}=g\left(X_{i}, Z_{i}\right)$ for each $i$. Although in principle, rewards may be random given the state, note that we can let $g$ be the expected reward in this case, so our definition is without loss of generality.

Estimand. The estimand of interest is the steady state difference in reward rate between global treatment and global control, i.e., the global treatment effect:

$$
\mathrm{GTE}=\sum_{x} \phi_{1}(x) g(x, 1)-\sum_{x} \phi_{0}(x) g(x, 0)
$$

Difference-in-means (DM) estimator and variance estimator. Both $\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}$ and $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$ are defined identically to the main text, cf. (5) and (6). As we consider only asymptotic results as $N \rightarrow \infty$ in our analysis in this section, we implicitly condition all our analysis on the (almost sure) event that $N_{1 N}>0$ and $N_{0 N}>N$.

Central limit theorem. We now state a central limit theorem for the difference-in-means estimator. To state the theorem, we require some additional notation. First define:

$$
\mathrm{ADE}_{a}=\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 1)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)
$$

The quantity $\mathrm{ADE}_{a}$ is the average direct effect [23]. Since, in general, this steady state distribution neither matches global treatment nor global control, in general $\mathrm{ADE}_{a} \neq \mathrm{GTE}$.

Next, define the following quantities for $z, z^{\prime} \in\{0,1\}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
V(z) & =\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(g\left(X_{1}, z\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, z)\right)^{2} \mid Z_{1}=z\right] \\
& =\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x)\left(g(x, z)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, z\right)\right)^{2} \\
& =\operatorname{Var}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left(Y_{1} \mid Z_{1}=z\right) \\
C_{j}\left(z, z^{\prime}\right) & =\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(g\left(X_{1}, z\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, z)\right)\left(g\left(X_{j}, z^{\prime}\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g\left(x, z^{\prime}\right)\right) \mid Z_{1}=z, Z_{j}=z^{\prime}\right] \\
& =\operatorname{Cov}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left(Y_{1}, Y_{j} \mid Z_{1}=z, Z_{j}=z^{\prime}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where we recall that $Y_{i}=g\left(X_{i}, Z_{i}\right)$. These quantities capture the conditional variance and covariance of rewards, respectively, given treatment assignments. Observe that although the expectations are with respect to the steady state distribution of $\left\{W_{i}\right\}$, i.e., $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}$, in fact $V(z)$ can be reduced to an expectation against the steady state distribution of $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$, i.e., $\boldsymbol{\phi}_{a}$. This is because the expectation only involves $X_{1}$, which is independent of $Z_{1}$. The same is true for $X_{1}$ in the definition of $C_{j}\left(z, z^{\prime}\right)$; however, $X_{j}$ in the definition of $C_{j}$ does depend on the initial treatment assignment $Z_{1}$.

We have the following theorem. The proof combines a standard Markov central limit theorem (e.g., [31], Theorem 1) with techniques for the central limit theorem of the difference-in-means estimator with i.i.d. observations (e.g., [56], Theorem 1.2).

Theorem A.1. Suppose $0<a<1$. Then regardless of the initial distribution, $\widetilde{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N} \rightarrow^{p} \mathrm{ADE}_{a}$ as $N \rightarrow \infty$, and $\widetilde{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}$ obeys the following central limit theorem as $N \rightarrow \infty$ :

$$
\sqrt{N}\left(\widetilde{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}-\mathrm{ADE}_{a}\right) \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}\left(0, \tilde{\sigma}_{a}^{2}\right)
$$

where:

$$
\tilde{\sigma}_{a}^{2}=\left(\frac{1}{1-a}\right) V(0)+\left(\frac{1}{a}\right) V(1)+2 \sum_{j>1} C_{j}(0,0)+C_{j}(1,1)-C_{j}(0,1)-C_{j}(1,0)
$$

with $\tilde{\sigma}_{a}^{2}>0$.
Proof. We first prove the convergence in probability of $\widetilde{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}$. Note that $N(1-a) / N_{0 N} \rightarrow^{p} 1$, and $N a / N_{1 N} \rightarrow^{p} 1$. Thus the ergodic theorem for Markov chains establishes that:

$$
\bar{Y}(0) \rightarrow^{p}\left(\frac{1}{1-a}\right) \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(1-Z_{1}\right) Y_{1}\right] ; \quad \bar{Y}(1) \rightarrow^{p}\left(\frac{1}{a}\right) \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[Z_{1} Y_{1}\right]
$$

Note that:

$$
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(1-Z_{1}\right) Y_{1}\right]=(1-a) \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[g\left(X_{1}, 0\right) \mid Z_{1}=0\right]=(1-a) \sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)
$$

similarly, $\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[Z_{1} Y_{1}\right]=a \sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 1)$. We conclude that:

$$
\bar{Y}(0) \rightarrow^{p} \sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0) ; \quad \bar{Y}(1) \rightarrow^{p} \sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 1)
$$

so that $\widehat{\mathrm{GT}_{\mathrm{E}}}_{N} \rightarrow^{p} \mathrm{ADE}_{a}$ as $N \rightarrow \infty$.
For $z \in\{0,1\}$ and $x \in S$, define:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& h_{1}(x, z)=\left(\frac{z}{a}\right)\left(g(x, 1)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, 1\right)\right) \\
& h_{0}(x, z)=\left(\frac{1-z}{1-a}\right)\left(g(x, 0)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, 0\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Observe that $h_{1}(x, 0)=h_{0}(x, 1)=0$. Further, observe that:

$$
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right)\right]=a \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{1}\left(X_{1}, 1\right) \mid Z_{1}=1\right]=\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[g\left(X_{1}, 1\right) \mid Z_{1}=1\right]-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 1)=0
$$

similarly, $\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right)\right]=0$.
For fixed, arbitrary $t_{0}, t_{1} \in \mathbb{R}$, define $h(z, x)=t_{0} h_{0}(x, z)+t_{1} h_{1}(x, z)$. Since $\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right)\right]=$ $\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right)\right]=0$, we have $\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right)\right]=0$ as well.

The standard central limit theorem for Markov chains (see, e.g., [31], Theorem 1) thus implies that:

$$
\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h\left(W_{i}\right) \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}\left(0, \gamma\left(t_{0}, t_{1}\right)^{2}\right)
$$

where:

$$
\gamma\left(t_{0}, t_{1}\right)^{2}=\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right)^{2}\right]+2 \sum_{j>1} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right) h\left(W_{j}\right)\right]
$$

Straightforward algebra gives the following identities:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right)^{2}\right]= & t_{0}^{2} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right)^{2}\right]+t_{1}^{2} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right)^{2}\right] \\
& +2 t_{0} t_{1} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right)\right] \\
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right) h\left(W_{j}\right)\right]= & t_{0}^{2} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{0}\left(W_{j}\right)\right]+t_{1}^{2} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{1}\left(W_{j}\right)\right] \\
& +t_{0} t_{1} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{1}\left(W_{j}\right)+h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{0}\left(W_{j}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Observe that for any realization of $W_{1}=\left(X_{1}, Z_{1}\right)$, we have $h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{1}\left(W_{1}\right)=0$, since either

$Z_{1}=0$ or $1-Z_{1}=0$. Further, observe that by conditioning on the realization of $Z_{1}$, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right)^{2}\right] & =\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(\frac{1-Z_{1}}{1-a}\right)^{2}\left(g\left(X_{1}, 0\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)\right)^{2}\right] \\
& =\left(\frac{1}{1-a}\right) \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(g\left(X_{1}, 0\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)\right)^{2} \mid Z_{1}=0\right] \\
& =\left(\frac{1}{1-a}\right) V(0)
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h_{0}\left(W_{1}\right) h_{0}\left(W_{j}\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(\frac{\left(1-Z_{1}\right)\left(1-Z_{j}\right)}{(1-a)^{2}}\right)\right. & \\
& \left.\cdot\left(g\left(X_{1}, 0\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)\right)\left(g\left(X_{j}, 0\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)\right)\right] & \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[\left(g\left(X_{1}, 0\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)\right)\left(g\left(X_{j}, 0\right)-\sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 0)\right) \mid Z_{1}=0, Z_{j}=0\right] & \\
& =C_{j}(0,0) .
\end{aligned}
$$

Using similar arguments, we arrive at the following identities:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right)^{2}\right] & =\left(\frac{t_{0}^{2}}{1-a}\right) V(0)+\left(\frac{t_{1}^{2}}{a}\right) V(1) \\
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[h\left(W_{1}\right) h\left(W_{j}\right)\right] & =t_{0}^{2} C_{j}(0,0)+t_{1}^{2} C_{j}(1,1)+t_{0} t_{1}\left(C_{j}(0,1)+C_{j}(1,0)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Now let $\left(U_{0}, U_{1}\right)$ be a jointly normally distributed random pair, with mean zero, and covariance matrix:

$$
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
V(0) /(1-a)+2 \sum_{j>1} C_{j}(0,0) & \sum_{j>1} C_{j}(0,1)+C_{j}(1,0) \\
\sum_{j>1} C_{j}(0,1)+C_{j}(1,0) & V(1) / a+2 \sum_{j>1} C_{j}(1,1)
\end{array}\right)
$$

We have shown that:

$$
t_{0}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h_{0}\left(W_{i}\right)\right)+t_{1}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h_{1}\left(W_{i}\right)\right) \Rightarrow t_{0} U_{0}+t_{1} U_{1}
$$

Using the Cramér-Wold device, we conclude that:

$$
\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h_{0}\left(W_{i}\right), \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h_{1}\left(W_{i}\right)\right) \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma})
$$

Define:

$$
\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{N}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{(N(1-a))}{N_{0 N}} \cdot \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h_{0}\left(W_{i}\right) \\
\frac{N a}{N_{1 N}} \cdot \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} h_{1}\left(W_{i}\right)
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{N_{0 N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(1-Z_{i}\right)\left(g\left(X_{i}, 0\right)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, 0\right)\right) \\
\frac{1}{N_{1 N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i}\left(g\left(X_{i}, 1\right)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, 1\right)\right)
\end{array}\right)
$$

Since $N(1-a) / N_{0 N} \rightarrow^{p} 1$, and $N a / N_{1 N} \rightarrow^{p} 1$, by Slutsky's theorem we have:

$$
\sqrt{N} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{N} \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma})
$$

Now observe that:

$$
\begin{aligned}
(-1,1)^{\top} \boldsymbol{\Gamma}_{N} & =\frac{1}{N_{1 N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i} g\left(X_{i}, 1\right)-\frac{1}{N_{0 N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(1-Z_{i}\right) g\left(X_{i}, 0\right) \\
& -\left(\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, 1\right)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi_{a}\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}, 0\right)\right) \\
& =\widehat{\mathrm{GT} E}_{N}-\mathrm{ADE}_{a}
\end{aligned}
$$

since $Z_{i} g\left(X_{i}, 1\right)=Z_{i} Y_{i}$ and $\left(1-Z_{i}\right) g\left(X_{i}, 0\right)=\left(1-Z_{i}\right) Y_{i}$. Straightforward algebra shows that $\tilde{\sigma}^{2}=(-1,1)^{\top} \Sigma(-1,1)$. Thus we have shown (29).

Limit of variance estimator. The following theorem gives the scaled limit of $\widehat{\mathrm{Var}}$.
Theorem A.2. Suppose $0<a<1$. Then $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$ satisfies

$$
N \widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N} \rightarrow^{p}\left(\frac{1}{a}\right) V(1)+\left(\frac{1}{1-a}\right) V(0)
$$

Note that in comparison to the true variance $\tilde{\sigma}^{2}$, the estimator misses all the covariance terms. Whether this is an overestimate or underestimate of the true variance depends on whether the within-group covariances are stronger are weaker than the across-group covariances, cf. (30).

Proof. We observe using a standard calculation that:

$$
\sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}(1)\right)^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i} Y_{i}^{2}-N_{1 N} \bar{Y}(1)^{2}
$$

From (31), we know that $\bar{Y}(1) \rightarrow^{p} \sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 1)$. We know $N_{1 N} /(N a) \rightarrow^{p} 1$ as $N \rightarrow \infty$, so by the ergodic theorem, we have:

$$
\frac{1}{N_{1 N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i} Y_{i}^{2} \rightarrow^{p} \frac{1}{a} \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[Z_{1} Y_{1}^{2}\right]
$$

We have:

$$
\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[Z_{1} Y_{1}^{2}\right]=a \mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\nu}_{a}}\left[g\left(X_{1}, 1\right)^{2} \mid Z_{1}=1\right]=a \sum_{x} \phi_{a}(x) g(x, 1)^{2}
$$

Finally, note that $N /\left(N_{1 N}-1\right) \rightarrow^{p} 1 / a$ as $N \rightarrow \infty$ as well. Combining all these facts, we conclude that:

$$
\frac{N}{\left(N_{1 N}-1\right) N_{1 N}} \sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i}\left(Y_{i}-\bar{Y}(1)\right)^{2} \rightarrow^{p} \frac{1}{a} V(1)
$$

An analogous calculation follows for the second term of $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$, establishing the claimed convergence of $N \widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$.

Note that the preceding result implies the t-test statistic centered at $\mathrm{ADE}_{N}$ given by $\left(\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}-\right.$ $\left.\operatorname{ADE}_{N}\right) / \sqrt{\operatorname{Var}_{N}}$ converges in distribution to a normal random variable with zero mean, and variance:

$$
\frac{V(0) /(1-a)+V(1) / a)}{V(0) /(1-a)+V(1) / a+2 \sum_{j>1} C_{j}(0,0)+C_{j}(1,1)-C_{j}(0,1)-C_{j}(1,0)}
$$

# A. 2 A/A experiments of Markov chains 

In this section, we apply our preceding results to $A / A$ experiments in a Markov chain setting. These are experiments where both the treatment and control chains are identical, the treatment assignment is completely independent of the Markov chain evolution; and where the rewards do not depend on treatment assignment. See also Section 4.1 for further discussion of A/A experiments.

Formally, we suppose that that there is a single irreducible transition matrix $P$ such that $P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid 0\right)=P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid 1\right)=P$; let $\phi$ be the invariant distribution of this matrix. This makes the evolution of $\left\{X_{i}\right\}$ independent of the realization of the treatment assignments $\left\{Z_{i}\right\}$. It follows that for all $a, 0 \leq a \leq 1$, we have $\phi_{a}=\phi$; and thus:

$$
\nu_{a}(x, z)=a^{z}(1-a)^{1-z} \phi(x)
$$

We also assume that there is a single reward function $g$ such that $g(x, 0)=g(x, 1)=g(x)$. Note that the resulting reward sequence $\left\{Y_{i}\right\}$ with $Y_{i}=g\left(X_{i}\right)$ is thus also independent of $\left\{Z_{i}\right\}$.

It follows from these definitions that for an $\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{A}$ test, $\mathrm{GTE}=\mathrm{ADE}_{a}=0$. We note also that with these definitions, we have:

$$
V=V(0)=V(1)=\sum_{x} \phi(x)\left(g(x)-\sum_{x^{\prime}} \phi\left(x^{\prime}\right) g\left(x^{\prime}\right)\right)^{2}
$$

Further, since all treatment assignments are independent of the states $\left(X_{1}, X_{j}\right)$, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{j} & =C_{j}(0,0)=C_{j}(1,1)=C_{j}(0,1)=C_{j}(1,0) \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{\boldsymbol{\phi}}\left[\left(g\left(X_{1}\right)-\sum_{x} \phi(x) g(x)\right)\left(g\left(X_{j}\right)-\sum_{x} \phi(x) g(x)\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where the notation $\mathbb{E}_{\phi}$ denotes that we take expectations with respect to the chain where the initial state $X_{1}$ is sampled from $\phi$. Combining Theorems A. 1 and A. 2 with these observations, we have the following result.

Theorem A.3. Suppose $0<a<1$. For an $A / A$ experiment, $\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}$ obeys the following central limit theorem as $N \rightarrow \infty$ :

$$
\sqrt{N \widehat{\mathrm{GTE}}}_{N} \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}\left(0,\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{1-a}\right) V\right)
$$

where $V$ is defined as in (33). In addition, $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$ satisfies

$$
N \widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N} \rightarrow^{p}\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{1-a}\right) V
$$

In particular, the t-test statistic converges in distribution to a standard normal random variable:

$$
\frac{\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}}_{N}}{\sqrt{\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}}} \Rightarrow \mathcal{N}(0,1)
$$

This result, when applied to general A/A tests in a Markov chain environment, can be used to demonstrate control of the false positive probability. In particular, suppose for each $N$ that the null hypothesis $\tilde{H}_{0}$ is defined as in (18), i.e., the null hypothesis assumes that the observations $Y_{1}, \ldots, Y_{N}$ are independent of $Z_{1}, \ldots, Z_{N}$. Further suppose the test statistic $\hat{T}_{N}$ is defined as in (14), and the decision rule (15) with the null hypothesis is $\tilde{H}_{0}$ is followed.

The corresponding false positive probability is the chance that $\tilde{H}_{0}$ is mistakenly rejected when it is true. Formally, this is:

$$
\mathrm{FPP}_{N}=\mathbb{P}\left(\hat{T}_{N}>\Phi_{\alpha / 2} \mid \tilde{H}_{0}\right)
$$

where the distribution of observations comes from the Markov chain and rewards defined by $P$ and $g$ respectively, with a fixed initial distribution. Note that $\mathrm{FPP}_{N}$ in (36) is well defined: Given that $Y_{1}, \ldots, Y_{N}$ are generated in this way, and $Z_{1}, \ldots, Z_{N}$ are i.i.d., as well as independent of $Y_{1}, \ldots, Y_{N}$ under $\tilde{H}_{0}$, the distribution of $\hat{T}_{N}$ is completely determined.

Theorem A. 3 then implies the following corollary.
Corollary A.1. Suppose $0<a<1$. Then for an $A / A$ experiment, as $N \rightarrow \infty, \mathrm{FPP}_{N} \rightarrow \alpha$, where $\mathrm{FPP}_{N}$ is defined as in (36).

The preceding result shows that for general A/A experiments in Markov chain environments, the false positive probability of the decision rule (15) is (asymptotically) controlled at level $\alpha$, as intended.

# A. 3 Cramér-Rao bound for A/B experiments of Markov chains 

In this section we present a result of [14], which uses the multivariate Cramér-Rao bound to provide a lower bound on the variance of any unbiased GTE estimator for an A/B experiment between two Markov chains. The same paper provides a least squares temporal difference (LSTD)based unbiased estimator that matches this lower bound. [19] present a nonparametric maximum likelihood estimator which also acheives the Cramér-Rao lower bound.

As in Section 5.2, in the general Markov chain setting we consider here, an estimator $\hat{\theta}_{N}$ is a real-valued functional of the observations $Y_{1}, \ldots, Y_{N}$ generated from a Bernoulli randomized experiment. We say that $\hat{\theta}_{N}$ is an unbiased estimator if for all feasible values of system parameters (i.e., $S, P, g$ ) and the design parameter $a$, there holds $\mathbb{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{N}\right]=$ GTE, where GTE is defined as in (28).

Theorem A. 4 ([14]). Let $\hat{\theta}_{N}$ be an unbiased estimator for GTE for all feasible values of system parameters (i.e., $S, P, g$ ) and the design parameter $a$. Then $\operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\theta}_{N}\right)$ satisfies

$$
\begin{aligned}
N \operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\theta}_{N}\right) & \geq \frac{1}{a} \sum_{x, x^{\prime}} \frac{\phi_{1}(x)^{2}}{\phi_{a}(x)} P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid 1\right)\left(v\left(x^{\prime} \mid 1\right)-v(x \mid 1)+g(x, 1)-\rho_{1}\right)^{2} \\
& +\frac{1}{1-a} \sum_{x, x^{\prime}} \frac{\phi_{0}(x)^{2}}{\phi_{a}(x)} P\left(x, x^{\prime} \mid 0\right)\left(v\left(x^{\prime} \mid 0\right)-v(x \mid 0)+g(x, 0)\right)-\rho_{0}\right)^{2}:=\sigma_{\mathrm{OB}}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

where for $z=0,1$ :

$$
\rho_{z}=\sum_{x} \phi_{z}(x) g(x, z)
$$

and:

$$
v(x \mid z)=\sum_{t=1}^{\infty} \mathbb{E}\left[g\left(X_{t}, Z_{t}\right)-\rho_{z} \mid X_{1}=x, Z_{t}=z \text { for all } t\right]
$$

In the preceding statement, $v(x \mid z)$ is the value function of either the global treatment condition (if $z=1$ ) or the global control condition (if $z=0$ ); the quantity $v(x \mid z)$ measures the cumulative difference between expected rewards and the steady state reward per time step.

We remark here that it is well known that $v$ solves Poisson's equation for the reward function $g$ :

$$
v(x \mid z)=g(x, z)-\rho_{z}+\sum_{x^{\prime}, y^{\prime}} P\left(x,, x^{\prime} \mid z\right) v\left(x^{\prime} \mid z\right)
$$

(See, e.g., [2].) The solution to Poisson's equation is uniquely specified only up to an additive constant. If we let $\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{z}$ be the stochastic matrix with $\boldsymbol{\phi}_{z}$ on every row, then one solution to Poisson's equation is obtained by:

$$
\mathbf{v}_{z}=\left(\mathbf{I}-\mathbf{P}_{z}+\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{z}\right)^{-1}\left(\mathbf{g}-\rho_{z} \mathbf{e}\right)
$$

where $\mathbf{I}$ is the identity matrix; $\mathbf{P}_{z}$ is the matrix with entries $P(\cdot, \cdot \mid z)$; $\mathbf{e}$ is the vector of 1 's; and $\mathbf{v}_{z}$ is the vector with entries $v(\cdot \mid z)$. This particular solution has the feature that $\sum_{x} \phi_{z}(x) v(x \mid z)=0$, which can be shown to hold for the definition in (38). The matrix $\left(\mathbf{I}-\mathbf{P}_{z}+\boldsymbol{\Phi}_{z}\right)^{-1}$ is the fundamental matrix of the Markov chain. We use this matrix formulation to compute the Cramér-Rao lower bound numerically in the main text.

# A. 4 Application to a capacity-constrained platform 

In this section we show that the model in Section 3 is a special case of the general Markov chain setting presented here, and can be analyzed using the same limit theorems.

To make the mapping, we must define appropriate discrete time Markov chains corresponding to global treatment and global control, and a corresponding reward function $g$. We proceed as follows. Following Section 3, let $X_{t}$ is the continuous time Markov chain of booked listings under global treatment (i.e., $a=1$ ). Let $T(i)$ be the arrival time of the $i^{\prime}$ th customer, and let $X_{T(i)}^{-}$ denote the state just before the arrival of the $i$ 'th customer. Let $S_{i}=\left(X_{T(i)}^{-}, Y_{i}\right)$. Note that $S_{i}$ is a stationary discrete-time Markov chain on the finite state space $\{0, \ldots, K\} \times\{0,1\}$ : given $S_{i}$, the next state $X_{T(i+1)}^{-}$is independent of the history prior to customer $i$, and of course given $X_{T(i+1)}^{-}$, the booking outcome $Y_{i+1}$ of customer $i+1$ is also independent of the history prior customer $i$.

We let $P\left(k, y, k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid 1\right)$ be the transition matrix of this discrete-time Markov chain corresponding to global treatment. Note that since Poisson arrivals see time averages (PASTA), the steady state distribution of $P(\cdot \mid 1)$ is:

$$
\phi_{1}(k, y)=\pi_{1}(k) p_{1}(k)^{y}\left(1-p_{1}(k)\right)^{1-y}
$$

We can similarly define $P\left(k, y, k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid 0\right)$ for the global control chain, with an analogous steady state distribution $\phi_{0}(k, y)$, and $P\left(k, y, k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid a\right)$ for the experimental chain, with an analogous steady state distribution $\phi_{a}(k, y)$.

Finally, for each state $k, y=0,1$, and $z=0,1$, define the reward function $g(k, y, z)=y$; this is the booking outcome. Note the difference in long run average reward between the treatment and control chains is:

$$
\sum_{k} \sum_{y=0,1} \phi_{1}(k, y) g(k, y)-\sum_{k} \sum_{y=0,1} \phi_{0}(k, y) g(k, y)=\sum_{k} \pi_{1}(k) p_{1}(k)-\sum_{k} \pi_{0}(k) p_{0}(k)=\mathrm{GTE}
$$

i.e., exactly the global treatment effect defined in (4). Thus the estimand in Section 3 is exactly the estimand in (28), i.e., the difference in long run average reward between the treatment and control discrete time chains with the primitives $P(\cdot \mid 1), P(\cdot \mid 0)$, and $g$ defined as in this section.

Thus Theorems A. 1 and A. 2 directly apply in the setting of Section 3, with the primitives defined as in this section. Applications of these results with the specific primitives defined above yields Theorems 3.1 and 3.2 in the main text. We remark here that it is important to carefully translate the expectations in the variances and covariances that appear in Theorem A.1. These are expectations evaluated with the initial distribution of the discrete-time chain initialized to $\pi_{1}$ or $\pi_{0}$ for global treatment and global control, respectively. In the continuous time Markov chain of Section 3, this corresponds to the requirement that the distribution of the state just prior to the arrival of the first customer is the steady state distribution $\pi_{1}$ or $\pi_{0}$.

Observe that if the null hypothesis $H_{0}: \mathrm{GTE}=0$ holds and the treatment is monotone, then by Proposition 3.1 we know that $p_{0}=p_{1}$, i.e., we are in the setting of an A/A experiment: both treatment and control Markov chains are identical. Theorem 4.1 in the main text then follows by applying Theorem A. 3 and Corollary A. 1 to the resulting A/A experiment.

Application of Theorem A. 4 yields the Cramér-Rao bound we leverage in Section 5.2, and in particular (23). In this setting, the Cramér-Rao bound in (37) becomes:

$$
\begin{aligned}
N \operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\theta}_{N}\right) \geq & \left(\frac{1}{a}\right) \sum_{k, y} \frac{\phi_{1}(k, y)^{2}}{\phi_{a}(k, y)} \sum_{k^{\prime}, y^{\prime}} P\left(k, y, k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid 1\right)\left(v\left(k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid 1\right)-v(k, y \mid 1)+g_{1}(k, y)-\rho_{1}\right)^{2} \\
& +\left(\frac{1}{1-a}\right) \sum_{k, y} \frac{\phi_{0}(k, y)^{2}}{\phi_{a}(k, y)}\left(\sum_{k^{\prime}, y^{\prime}} P\left(k, y, k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid 0\right)\left(v\left(k^{\prime}, y^{\prime} \mid 0\right)-v(k, y \mid 0)+g_{0}(k, y)-\rho_{0}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \triangleq \sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $v(k, y \mid z)$ is the value function for $z=0,1$ associated to the reward function $g$ defined above, with $\rho_{z}=\sum_{k} \pi_{z}(k) p_{z}(k)$.

We conclude this section with the proof of Theorem 5.3, which establishes exponential growth of $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ generically in the size of the state space.

$$
\tilde{\lambda} \bar{p}_{z}(s)=\bar{\tau}(s)
$$

for $z=0, a$. It is easy to check that $0<s_{0}^{*}<s_{a}^{*}$, given the monotonicity properties of $\bar{p}_{0}, \bar{p}_{1}, \bar{\tau}$, and the fact that treatment is monotone. $$

$$

$$
\pi_{0}^{(K)}(k)<\pi_{0}^{(K)}\left(k_{0}^{\prime}\right) \cdot c_{1}^{k-k_{0}^{\prime}}<c_{1}^{k_{0}^{+}-k_{0}^{\prime}}
$$

Since this is true for all $k \geq k_{0}^{+}$, we conclude that:

$$
\sum_{k=k_{0}^{+}}^{K} \pi_{0}^{(K)}(k)^{2}<c_{2} c_{1}^{2\lfloor\epsilon K\rfloor}
$$

for a constant $c_{2}>0$ and all sufficiently large $K$. To see this, observe that there are less than $K$ terms in the first sum, and each term is bounded above by $c_{1}^{2\left(k_{0}^{+}-k_{0}^{\prime}\right)}$. Given the definitions of $k_{0}^{\prime}, k_{0}^{+}$ and the fact that $c_{1}<1$, we can choose an appropriate constant $c_{2}$ for the stated bound.

Similarly, let $k_{0}^{-}=\left\lceil\left(s_{0}^{*}-3 \epsilon\right) K\right\rceil$. We can use an analogous argument to conclude that there exist constants $c_{3}<1$ and $c_{4}>0$ such that:

$$
\sum_{k=0}^{k_{0}^{-}} \pi_{0}^{(K)}(k)^{2}<c_{4} c_{3}^{2\lfloor\epsilon K\rfloor}
$$

We omit the details. Taken together, note that we have:

$$

If $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i-1}^{\mathbf{0}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i-1}^{\mathbf{Z}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i-1}^{\mathbf{1}}$, and $Z_{i-1}=0$, then we can show that $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{0}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{Z}}$ using (DR4), combined with (48) and (49). We can show that $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{Z}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}}$ using (DR5), combined with (48) and (49). Thus again (3) holds.

In all cases we have shown that one of (1), (2), or (3) holds. Finally, since $N_{0}>1$ and $N_{1}>1$, it follows from our derivation that there must be at least one customer for whom (3) holds, and for all subsequent customers (3) holds. This completes the proof.

Proof of Corollary 5.1. If the first customer arrives to find the queue in $\pi_{0}$ (i.e., $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\pi_{0}$ ) and $Z_{i}=0$ for all $i$, then we remain in the global control system for all customers. Therefore every subsequent customer also arrives to find the queue in $\pi_{0}$ by the PASTA (Poisson arrivals see time averages) property. Thus in this case $\pi_{i}^{\mathbf{0}}=\pi_{0}$ for all $i$. If instead $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\pi_{1}$, then $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}}=\pi_{1}$ for all $i$.

Now suppose that $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\pi_{0}$. We adopt the same notation and definitions as the proof of Proposition 5.1. Consider customer 2. Using (DR1), (48), and (49), it follows that $\pi_{0}=\boldsymbol{\nu}_{2}^{\mathbf{0}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{2}^{\mathbf{1}}$. With this as the base case, now suppose the inductive hypothesis holds that $\pi_{0}=\boldsymbol{\nu}_{j}^{\mathbf{0}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{j}^{\mathbf{1}}$ for all customers $j=2, \ldots, i-1$. By using (DR5) we obtain $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i-1}^{\mathbf{1} \dagger} \succ^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i-1}^{\mathbf{0} \dagger}$. Combining with (48) and (49), we obtain $\pi_{0}=\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{0}} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}}$. Thus $\pi_{0} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}}$ for all $i$.

To complete the proof, take limits as $i \rightarrow \infty$ in case (3) of Proposition 5.1. By PASTA, we have $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{0}} \rightarrow \pi_{0}$, and $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}} \rightarrow \pi_{1}$. Thus $\pi_{0} \prec^{d} \pi_{1}$. Now suppose we let $\psi=\pi_{0}$, and $\phi=\pi_{1}$. Then applying (DR3), together with (48) and (49), we conclude that if $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\pi_{0}$, then $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{2}^{\mathbf{1}} \prec^{d} \pi_{1}$. We can continue in this way, inductively applying (DR3) together with (48) and (49), to conclude that if $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\pi_{0}$, then $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}} \prec^{d} \pi_{1}$ for all $i>1$.

A similar set of arguments can be used to establish that if $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\pi_{1}$, then $\pi_{0} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{0}} \prec^{d} \pi_{1}$ for all $i>1$; we omit the details. This completes the proof.

Proof of Theorem 5.1. We start by noting that given a treatment assignment vector $\mathbf{Z}$, if customer $i$ has treatment status $Z_{i}=z$ and sees state distribution $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{Z}}$ on arrival, then:

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i} \mid \mathbf{Z}\right]=\sum_{k} \nu_{i}^{\mathbf{Z}}(k) p_{z}(k)
$$

We define one additional piece of notation that will be useful for this proof. If $\boldsymbol{\phi}, \boldsymbol{\psi}$ are two distributions on $\{0, \ldots, K\}$, then we write $\boldsymbol{\phi} \succeq^{d} \boldsymbol{\psi}$ if either $\boldsymbol{\phi} \succ^{d} \boldsymbol{\psi}$ or $\boldsymbol{\phi}=\boldsymbol{\psi}$.

Now let $\boldsymbol{\zeta}$ denote a treatment assignment vector with $\sum_{i=1}^{N} \zeta_{i}=N_{1}>0$, and $N_{0}=N-N_{1}>0$. Recall that $\boldsymbol{\nu}_{1}=\boldsymbol{\pi}_{0}$, by Assumption 5.1. Combining Corollary 5.1 with Proposition 5.1, we can conclude that for all $i$ :

$$
\boldsymbol{\pi}_{0}=\boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{0}} \preceq^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\boldsymbol{\zeta}} \preceq^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\mathbf{1}} \preceq^{d} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{1}
$$

In particular, for any customer $i$, we have:

$$
\boldsymbol{\pi}_{0} \preceq^{d} \boldsymbol{\nu}_{i}^{\boldsymbol{\zeta}} \preceq^{d} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{1}
$$

Now for any customer $i$ with $\zeta_{i}=1$, if we take the expectation of $\mathbf{p}_{1}$ in the second relation in (51) and consider (50), then we obtain:

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i} \mid \mathbf{Z}=\boldsymbol{\zeta}\right] \geq \sum_{k} \pi_{1}(k) p_{1}(k)=\rho_{1}
$$

Similarly, for any customer $i$ with $\zeta_{i}=0$, if we take the expectation of $\mathbf{p}_{0}$ in the first relation in (51) and consider (50), then we obtain:

$$
\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i} \mid \mathbf{Z}=\boldsymbol{\zeta}\right] \leq \sum_{k} \pi_{0}(k) p_{0}(k)=\rho_{0}
$$

Note that there must be a customer $i$ such that case (3) of Proposition 5.1 holds for all $j \geq i$, it is straightforward to check that for all these customers $j$, the corresponding inequality in (52)-(53) is strict.

Thus we conclude that:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{E}[\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}} \mid \mathbf{Z}=\boldsymbol{\zeta}] & =\frac{1}{N_{1}} \sum_{i} \zeta_{i} \mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i} \mid \mathbf{Z}=\boldsymbol{\zeta}\right]-\frac{1}{N_{0}} \sum_{i}\left(1-\zeta_{i}\right) \mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i} \mid \mathbf{Z}=\boldsymbol{\zeta}\right] \\
& >\rho_{1}-\rho_{0}=\mathrm{GTE}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since this holds for every $\boldsymbol{\zeta}$ with $N_{1}>0$ and $N_{0}>0$, we conclude:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}} \mid N_{1}>0, N_{0}>0]>\mathrm{GTE}
$$

Finally, note that since $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{1} \succ^{d} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{0}$ by Corollary 5.1, and the treatment is strictly positive, it follows that GTE $>0$. All the assertions are reversed if the treatment is strictly negative, completing the proof.

Proof of Theorem 5.2. We first show that for any $0<a<1$ we have $\boldsymbol{\pi}_{0} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{a} \prec^{d} \boldsymbol{\pi}_{1}$. We use Proposition 5.1 together with the PASTA property (Poisson arrivals see time averages). Let $Z_{1}, Z_{2}, \ldots$ be an i.i.d. Bernoulli(a) sequence. Suppose Assumption 5.1 holds. Let $N_{1 N}=\sum_{i=1}^{N} Z_{i}$,

and let $N_{0 N}=N-N_{1 N}$. Let $\mathbf{Z}_{N}=\left(Z_{1}, \ldots, Z_{N}\right)$. Observe that from Proposition 5.1, it follows that:

$$
\nu_{i}^{0} \prec^{d} \mathbb{E}\left[\nu_{i}^{\mathbf{Z}_{i}} \mid N_{0 i}>0, N_{1 i}>0\right] \prec^{d} \nu_{i}^{\mathbf{1}}
$$

where the expectation is only over the randomness in $\mathbf{Z}_{i}$. Further, observe that $\mathbb{E}\left[\nu_{i}^{\mathbf{Z}_{i}}\right]$ is the state distribution just prior to the arrival of the $i$ 'th customer in a Bernoulli $(a)$ CR experiment. Taking $N \rightarrow \infty$, noting that $P\left(N_{0 i}=0\right.$ or $\left.N_{1 i}=0\right) \rightarrow 0$ as $N \rightarrow \infty$, and applying PASTA, we conclude that:

$$
\pi_{0} \prec^{d} \pi_{a} \prec^{d} \pi_{1}
$$

Now note that Assumption 3.1 implies

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sum_{k} p_{1}(k) \pi_{a}(k)>\sum_{k} p_{1}(k) \pi_{1}(k) \\
& \sum_{k} p_{0}(k) \pi_{0}(k)>\sum_{k} p_{0}(k) \pi_{a}(k)
\end{aligned}
$$

which allows us to conclude that

$$
\mathrm{ADE}_{a}=\sum_{k}\left(p_{1}(k)-p_{0}(k)\right) \pi_{a}(k)>\sum_{k} p_{1}(k) \pi_{1}(k)-\sum_{k} p_{0}(k) \pi_{0}(k)=\mathrm{GTE}
$$

# C Statistical power: Additional numerics 

In this section, we report additional numerical results in the setting of Section 5.2, by visualizing performance across variation in a wider range of parameters. In Section C.2, we present additional numerical results comparing the Cramér-Rao lower bound $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ to the true variance of $\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}}$ as well as the variance estimator $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}$. In Section C. 3 we present present additional numerical results comparing statistical power of the decision rule (15) using the test statistic $\hat{T}_{N}$ (cf. (14)) as compared to the same rule using any unbiased test statistic $\hat{U}_{N}$ (cf. (22)). In all cases studied, we find that if the state space is sufficiently large, we observe that $\sigma_{\mathrm{UB}}^{2}$ is much larger than either $\operatorname{Var}(\widehat{\mathrm{GTE}})$ or $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}$, and correspondingly that the power obtained is significantly higher using $\hat{T}_{N}$ instead of $\hat{U}_{N}$.

# C. 1 Setup 

Throughout the numerics in this section, we consider the following values for the model parameters:

$$
\begin{aligned}
K & =200 \\
\tau^{(K)} & =K \cdot \bar{\tau} \mathbf{1} \text { with } \bar{\tau}=1 \\
\lambda^{(K)} & =K \cdot \bar{\lambda} \text { with } \bar{\lambda}=1.5 \\
\epsilon^{(K)} & =K \cdot \bar{\epsilon} \text { with } \bar{\epsilon}=1.0 \\
a & =0.5 \\
v_{0} & =0.5 \\
v_{1} & =v_{0}+\delta \text { with } \delta=0.05 \\
p_{0}^{(K)}(k) & =\frac{(K-k) v_{0}}{\epsilon^{(K)}+(K-k) v_{0}} \\
p_{1}^{(K)}(k) & =\frac{(K-k) v_{1}}{\epsilon^{(K)}+(K-k) v_{1}}
\end{aligned}
$$

The values of $\bar{\lambda}, \bar{\tau}$, and $K$ were chosen to ensure that the system is large and has sufficient interference between customers. The values of $v_{0}, \delta$, and $\bar{\epsilon}$ were chosen to produce a small treatment effect; in this case we have $\widehat{\mathrm{~L} T E}=0.022$.

In all the numerics in this section, $a$ and $v_{0}$ are fixed. In each set of numerics, we fix all but one of the model parameters $K, \bar{\lambda} / \bar{\tau}, \bar{\epsilon}, \delta$, and vary the held out parameter.

## C. 2 Variance comparisons under monotone treatments

In this section, compute the scaled limit of $\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{N}$ from Theorem A. 2 and the lower bound on $\sigma_{\widehat{\mathrm{UB}}}^{2}$ from Theorem A. 4 in Bernoulli randomized CR experiments with each of $K, \lambda / \tau, \bar{\epsilon}, \delta$ varying, and the other parameters fixed as described above. In Figure 5, we see that the bound on the variance of an unbiased estimator is larger than the true variance of $\widehat{\mathrm{GT} E}$ regardless of how we vary the model parameters.

## C. 3 Power comparisons under monotone treatments

In this section, we use the CLT from Theorem 3.1 and the power calculation (25) to compute the false negative probability of the naive test statistic and any unbiased test statistic that obeys (24). From Figures 6, 7, 8, and 9, we see that the decision rule using the test statistic $\hat{T}_{N}$ (cf. (14)) exhibits higher power than the same rule using any unbiased test statistic $\hat{U}_{N}$. In particular, the FNP of the test statistic $\hat{T}_{N}$ decays at a faster rate as $N$ increases in all cases.

abstract:
This paper investigates decision-making in A/B experiments for online
platforms and marketplaces. In such settings, due to constraints on inventory,
A/B experiments typically lead to biased estimators because of interference;
this phenomenon has been well studied in recent literature. By contrast, there
has been relatively little discussion of the impact of interference on
decision-making. In this paper, we analyze a benchmark Markovian model of an
inventory-constrained platform, where arriving customers book listings that are
limited in supply; our analysis builds on a self-contained analysis of general
A/B experiments for Markov chains. We focus on the commonly used frequentist
hypothesis testing approach for making launch decisions based on data from
customer-randomized experiments, and we study the impact of interference on (1)
false positive probability and (2) statistical power.
  We obtain three main findings. First, we show that for monotone treatments --
i.e., those where the treatment changes booking probabilities in the same
direction relative to control in all states -- the false positive probability
of the na\"ive difference-in-means estimator with classical variance estimation
is correctly controlled. This result stems from a novel analysis of A/A
experiments with arbitrary dependence structures. Second, we demonstrate that
for monotone treatments, when the state space is large, the statistical power
of this na\"ive approach is higher than that of any similar pipeline using a
debiased estimator. Taken together, these two findings suggest that platforms
may be better off not debiasing when treatments are monotone. Finally, we
numerically investigate false positive probability and statistical power when
treatments are non-monotone, and we show that the performance of the na\"ive
approach can be arbitrarily worse than a debiased approach in such cases.
